<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Ok, I read through all this (gee I must be bored  <IMG SRC="wink.gif" border="0">) and I *can* see both sides points.<P>*Maybe* I can make some common ground hehe<P>Swapping in and out buffs isnt stategy, it is just tedious. Verant *do* want to reduce tedium if they can, the interface has been improved many times to that end.<P>There *is* some strategy to deciding which offensive spells to mem in a situation. It isnt rocket science or grandmaster chess, but it is there.<P>As a cleric I would love to always have 3 or 4 stuns up, it would just make my life so much easier, but I can rarely ever afford that luxery.<P>Usually I have 4 heals, stun, root, and 2 invulns. That means that if a mob tries to gate, I have a single chance to stop it. If I get resisted, I *would* have time to cast a second stun if I had it up.<P>To have that second stun I need to drop root, a heal, or an invuln.<BR>Dropping root means I cant help with crowd control.<BR>Dropping an invuln is a risk for my whole group if I get aggro'd and they cant get it off me.<BR>Dropping a heal speaks for itself.<P>What would *probably* satisfy both parties here would be to have a second bank of spells (or more) that could only have non-offensive spells (buffs) memmed in.<P>Verant has already marked out spells as offensive or buffs, since you cant cast buffs on NPCs, and you cant cast offensive spells on PCs (usually).<P>An alternative would be to add some extra casting time to the second and subsequent banks - say 2 or 3 seconds. But that could be an irritant in itself for those classes that buff a lot - they might just put the buff on the first bank anyway then  <IMG SRC="tongue.gif" border="0"><P>--------------------<P>Elasto, 57 Cleric
</FONT>
